{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_india_ver02/data/sn83045433/100493445/1908042601/0352.xml":{"full_text":"E BUILDING SECTION\nWASHINGTON, D. C.,, SUNDAY, APRIL 26, 1908.\nJF AT WASHINGTON HERALD\n=a Thind Pare art: EAL \\LAL EST STA\nTRADE CONDITIONS\nON A SOUND BASIS\nmonths to come, believing that his busi- ing the last twenty years.\nness was bound to grow and bring better When the spirit had gone through the\nWashington Merchants Are\nHopeful About Outlook.\nmerchant of Washington has to I J 4 Sri\nGOODS MOVING FREELY\nNo Despondent Note Struck by\nAny Business Man.\nResults of Last Year's Financial\nFlurry Practically Discounted in\nRetail Trade\u2014Proprietors of Stores\nState Their Views Freely\u2014Money\nCollected and Crediis Do Not As\nsume a Very Large Volume,\nWHET ana CUrediis Uo Not As\nsume a Very Large Volume,\nWashington merchants are not suffer\ning despondency this spring on account\nOf trade conditions. They find business\ngood, better than they expected it would\nbe a few weeks ago, and the majority of\nthem interviewed during the past week\nby The Washington Herald reporter had\nonly cheerful things to say of the out\nlook,\nI\n\niH\ni\n3 {8 iil\n18 i\nHi\n1 HT HB\nHi if i\ni fii I\niil\nLl i {1 if\ni LH fy\nIn a few instances the reporter was told\nthat the volume of business has not been\nquite so large as last year, but in many\nothers\u00abthe contrary was stated to be true,\nand all through the great department\nStores and in the smaller places of busi\ni i i i\ni\ni\ni f\ni\nti\na\n\n\nness the feeling is that the stagnation\nIncident to the financial depression of\nlast October is now a thing of the past,\nthat business is really improving, and\nthat the retail trade of the city is on a\nsolid footing from which it will not be\nshaken.\n1 MN i\n\nfi i\n\nJ WIL\nL\u2014\u2014iio T\nif\n[i J\nA Tew expressed the opinion that real\nimprovement would come after the Presi\ndential election in the fall, but the ma\nJority of the merchants said frankly that\nthey did not see that politics had any per\nceptible ipfluence upon trade in Wash\nington.\ni\ni\ni\n\nYY\n\n\n\ni\ni\n{IE\nI\nLi\nBusiness Brisk This Month,\nNN\nThe manager of one of the large de\npartment stores stated that business in\nhis store had been good through the win\nter and was particularly brisk just now.\nHe said that in comparing the volume of\nbusiness in March last year with that in\nthe same month this year there was a\nsmall decrease, but he attributed it to\nthe fact that Easter fell in March last\nYear and in April this year. He said that\nwhen the balance sheets were made up at\nthe end of this menth they would prob\nably show that a considerable advance\nhad been made in April over last year,\nand he was expecting that the combined\ntrade of the two months this year would\n\n\ni i\nLC es\nco ou\ni\n1 a NLETEIVY; IY IR IY CC AAAI LA J\n\nr y 5 lt\npL F R TE 0) G 2 T 1 F 71\n4 i \u2014_\u2014 wil A A 2 IR\nj HL. Y\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nA\nshow a fair margin of increase over the\nsame two months last year.\n\na\nOne of the noticeable views expressed\nwas that business would not suffer any\nset-backs during the balance of the\nspring and summer as compared with for\nmer years. \u2018The manager of one of the.\nsmalier stores had just returned from\nNew York, and he said the opinion of all\nthe leading merchants there of his ac\nquaintance was that the reaction incident\nto the financial flurry of last year had\nbeen fully -discounted and that trade\nwould go on with increasing momentum\nfrom this time forward.\nsnd\n\nJ\n\n\n\n\nsen mm\n\ni\n\n\nCredit Not Expanded,\n\nThe question of credits was discussed\nwith several of the merchants. They\nstated that it had been necessdry to fol\nlow up the collection of accounts with a\nlittle more vigor this year than was the\ncase last year, and that with the added\nattention given to the matter the amount\nof money collected on outstanding ac\ncounts had been as great as in former\nyears, None of the merchants would say\nthat any greater volume of credits had\nbeen extended this year than formerly;\nin fact, in several instances the reverse\nwas said to be the fact.\n4\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\ni\n\n\nSAME\n\\fals ohm\no-all, QUATIETS. covvnvniiiiiinnnnen,\nUnmalted grain, quarters\n\nhundred we t i\nMerchants generally in Washington are\nof the opinion that trade is rapidly re\nturning to normal conditions, It wag\nstated that it really had never been far\nremoved from that condition here. The\nmajority of customers in Washington\neither pay cash for what they buy or\ncredit is extended only for the month\nfollowing that of purchase. This, in trade\nparlance, is equivalent to cash trade, as\nthe great majority of outstanding ac\ncounts are settled within thirty days, few\nof them running so long as sixty days.\nPersons employed by the government re\nceive their salaries regularly in cash and\nare enabled to pay their bills with the\nsame regularity in bad times as in good\ntimes, x\nMalt extrac aed ht Ia\nENGLAND,\nsate quarters L35\naia 8 H \u00a3254] \u201cau 81.2:\nUnmalted grain dh LE 253.314\nj Rise, Banas we\nMola eo AAA TET TEPER 950\n|g es, hundredweight 4 go\nredweight 2\nel weight SR sa 151\nedweight 35:\nTapio, hundredweig 1303\na i ET NS\nMalt combings, hundre dweight. TARE Co 0 SOAS\n1% arters FRSLAND.\nUnmalted grain QUARIEES esssreuse re vrere..\nSmaller Stocks the Rule,\nOne merchant stated that the maln dif\nference between business now and a year\nago was to be found in smaller stocks in\nthe stores, quicker disposal of merchan\ndise on hand, and a more frequent turn\ning over of the money invested, The\nmerchant who said this declared it was a\nmore healthful condition than that which|\nprevailed last year, in that it brought|\nbusiness a little nearer to a cash basis,\nwhich is universally recognized as the\n{deal condition.\n\nRetail merchants this spring are finding\nproof that the circle of trade is widen~\ning. Not only are there more customers\nin the city itself, but more are coming\nthis year from the near-by territory in\nthe State of Virginia and Maryland than\nin former years. This is attributed in\npart to the special inducements offered\nby the local merchants last fall in the\n\u201ctrade weeks\u201d movement, which ac\nquainted buyers at some distance from\nthe city with the advantages of buying\nsupplies in the stores of Washington.\nD. A. R, Delegates Purchasers,\nOne of the noticeable features of the\ntrade of last week in many of the stores\n\u2018was the buying of many pretty things for\npersonal use for gifts by the women in\n\u2018attendance upon the convention of the D.\nA. R. The merchants find that this tran\nsient trade from the outside has become\na factor in their business, and not a few\nMs A hi Za ARE ardid al  Rauah gual\nA BO AR el ee\nAfter a careful survey of the field and\nafter talking with representative mer\nchants in all lines of trade, the econclu\nof\nsion was forced that who is\nspring,\nlvl BEE\nto do what he can to bring this trade td\n3 Wu\nhis share of trade and doing well this\nMr. Lisner Is Hopeful,\nA Lisner, proprietor of the Palais\nRoyal, stated that business in his store\nFa\never Defore. He said there had been at\nAN0 UUme any cessation of trade with him.\nfear either from present conditions or the\nPresidential election to follow in the fall.\nIn Mr. Lisner's view this political bogie\nhas been overworked. He does not be\nHleve it has anywhere the effect in un\nseftling trade that it is credited with,\nAnyhow, he expects the Palais Royal to\nride through it without straining a seam\nor parting a sail\nMr. Lisner was very confident that the by 3 second gis\n\nSamuel Ross, of Barber Ross, stated\nthat the hardware business had suffered\na good deal for the past six months be\ncause of the great decrease in building\noperations, Trade, he said, had been\npicking up for the past month, and he\n\u2018thought it would probably improve dur\nog the summer months, Mr. Ross was\nin no way dispondent over the situation,\nstating that he simply wanted to explain\nthe special conditions which confronted\nthe hardware trade before expressing any\nopinion upon the outlook.\n\nShoes Are Selling Well.\nAndrew Betts, manager for Edmonston\nCo., dealers. in shoes, was In a hopeful\nmood when called upon by the reporter.\nMr. Betts and all his clerks were busy\nwaiting upon customers, and he twisted\na stretcher in a lady's shoe as he said\nthat business had never been better in\nthe shoe trade, and that he wag ncw\nhaving about all he could find time tg do,\nand that his store had been crowded with\nwell-paying patrons all through the win\nter and spring. Mr. Betts stated that he\nwas selling more \u201cFoot Form shoes\u201d\nthan ever before in the history of the\nbusiness.\nJohn Henry Small, the Fourteenth\nstreet florist, stated that business in the\nmain had been very good over the Eas\nter holidays and that everything was\npromising for the balance of the spring\nmonths. Mr. Small said there were fash\nons in flowers and flowering plants, as\nin everything else, and he said that hap\npily his house had been able to cater to\nthe prevailing fashion of the spring and\nhad done well, Mr. Small is firm in the\nbelief that business conditions will im\nprove, and he looks for a great season\n\u00bbf trade in the months to come, when\nthe finances of the country have had op\nportunity to find full adiustnent.\nWilliam F. Gude, of Gude Brother,\nstated that the trade of his company had\nbeen excellent, especially the Easter\nrade. He thought that business had in\n\u2018reased very materially in the last two\nmonths, and he expressed the opinion\nhat there would be no let-up in the prosg\n\u2018ess of better times until everything was\nigain at the recognized normal level.\nNo Slump in Furniture,\nArthur Moses, of W, B, Moses Sons,\nstated that business was at least 10 to 15\nper cent better than he expected it would\nbe. Mr. Moses stated that sales had\nzone along well for the months of March\nand April, and he felt that at the rate at\nwhich trade had been picking up the re\nurns of the year would be quite as good\n1s the average twelve months. Mr. Moses\nloes not expect any disturbing conditions\n0 appear within the next few months.\nHe stated that his company had collected\nnore money this spring and had extended\n10 more eredit than at other times. Mr.\nMoses thought that all the business ther\nnometers and barometers were regis\nered at the favorable marks for the bal\nnee of the year.\ni i\nGoldenbergs are not only doing a good\njusiness, but report that their trade is\nrowing all the time in a most gratifying\nnanner. Their advertising brings from\nnonth to month a larger clientele to their\nig stores in Seventh street, and they\nail to see any signs in the sky other than\nopeful ones,\nA. T. Marks stated for Hecht\n0. that the business of their house\nyas surely on the up grade. March and\n.pril particularly have been good months\nvith them, and the proprietors are in a\nopeful frame of mind regarding the out\nyok for the balance of the year.\nMany other merchants talked with!\night be quoted, but it would be only to\napeat what has been said. Washington\nierchants see no reason for discourage\nnent, and business is moving forward\nith a steady motion that will show good\nsults when the profits of the year 1908\nre counted up.\nee BB EYE. Ea BE\nTHEY SEEK VIRGINIA.\nHome Buyers Attracted to Hills of\nthe Neighboring Counties\nthe Neighboring Counties,\n\"More persons have visited the Virginia\nside of the Potomac this spring than\never before,\u201d said Mr. Collins, the real\nestate broker of Clarendon, Va. to a\nreporter for The Washington Herald re\ncently. \u201cI do not mean as visitors,\u201d he\ncontinued, \u2018but as prospective purchasers\nof homes.\n\u201cIn years gone by the transportation\nfacilities were poor, but now, with the\naid of the electric lines, Alexandria and\nFairfax counties are rapidly filling up\nwith home buyers. It is a fact that a\nperson can get to almost any part of\nAlexandria County quicker than to the\noutskirts of Washington, eliminating en\ntirely the suburbs of the city.\n\u201cPersons come into my office and ex\npress astonishment when I tell them they\ncan get home from thelr work in a few\nminutes. Then there are other attractive\nfeatures about Alexandria County that\nappeal strongly to the homeseeker\u2014pure\nair, pure water, and cheap land.\n\u201cRealty operators feel much encour\naged, and it is freely predicted that our\npopulation will more than double in three\nvears.\u201d\nStone Fairfax have sold for Thomas\nKeefe the two-story and cellar brick\nhouse at 148 U street northwest. The\nhouse contains eight rooms, and is under\niease. Dr, Thomas McConville is the\npurchaser and will take possession at the\nexpiration of the lease, occupying the\nhouse for his home. Mr. Keefe not long\nago bought the property through Stone\nFairfax.\nOlive R. Brown and Caroline E. Miller\nhave bought from John C. McKericher the\nnew two-story and basement brick house\nat 2101 Fiagler street northwest. The\nprice paid for the property was $4,150. The\nsale was made by Willige, Gibbs Dan\nial\nU Street House Briugs 24.500.\nShannon Luchs have sold the two\nstory brick house at 144 U street north\nwest to James Maddux. The house has\neight rooms. The price paid was $4,500,\nand it is the intention of the purchaser to\noccupy it as his home.\nof them expressed the opinion that it be\nhooves the retail merchant in the future\nwill Occupy Property sas Home\nMoore Hill have sold for Nobile J.\nThomas premises 1115 E street northeast.\nThe improvements consist of a two-story\nbrick dwelling. The purchaser will oc\ncupy the house as a residence.\nconfidently going after business by con\nsistent and careful advertising is getting\nWhile you think of it, telephone your\nWant Ad. to The Washington Herald, and\nbill will be sent you at 1 cent a word.\nhad been better this year so far than|\nSell House in 17 Street\nHouse Brings 84 150\nBarnard Childress Give Special\nAttention to Apariment Houses.\nBarnard Childress Give Special\nAttention to Apariment Houses,\nBarnard Childress, with offices at\n1412 G street northwest, was organized in\nApril, 197, and is just one year old. The\npresident of the company had a careful\ntraining in the fundamentals of the real\nestate business through several years\u2019\nconnection with the property department\nof the Washington Loan and Trust Com\npany. In the new firm he looks after the\nsales department, and is building up a\nfine business.\nThe treasurer and secretary studied the\nrental problem in this city in one of the\nlocal offices, which is reputed to have\none of the largest rental lists {in Wash\nington\u2014one which takes in all kinds of\nproperty, in all sections of the District of\nColumbia. Mr. Childress brought this\nknowledge and experience to bear upon\nthe rental management of a number of\napartment houses, which the firm took\nover as the foundation of their business.\nThe company is particularly interested\nin this class of property, having on their\nlist high-grade, but reasonably priced,\napartments, in the rental of which the\nfirm has been very successful. This firm\nhas contracts for the management of\nseveral new houses of this character now\nunder construction,\nSHREWD IN REAL ESTATE.\nPresident of Barnard Childress, is\nnative of Washington, and was for five\nyears connected with the Washington\nLoan and Trust Company. Mr. Barnard\nstarted in business for himself in 1903, as\na member of the firm of Barnard\nMark. That firm later dissolved, and he\nwas alone until April, 197, when the\nfirm of Barnard Childress was estab\nlished. Mr. Barnard is thirty-one years\nold and is married.\nFOURTEENTH STREET IMPROVEMENT.\nV4\nrr ouusss had ett fist he os te oa ont 88 the price was\nand his chief helpers had expected, and ised ne as TE\nDesigned by Frank H. Jackson; Ruilders, Jones Peters.\nTHEY RENT FLATS.\nCLARENCE BARNARD.\nWILL ERECT SIX HOUSES.\nLewis E., Breuninger Buys Ground\nfor Them in Monroe Street\nLewis EE. Breuninger Buys Ground\nfor Them in Monroe Street.\nThomas J. Fisher Co. report the\nsale of the last of the five houses on the\nnorth side of Monroe street, just east of\nFourteenth street, which are now being\nbuilt by Lewis E. Breuninger. Mr Breun\nInger took title to the ground January\n14, and the houses are not yet quite fin\nished.\nMr. Breuninger has bought six addi\ntional lots on Monroe street, at the cor\nner of Holmead avenue, and is now\nerecting six houses, which will be offered\nexclusively for sale by Fisher Co., the\ncorner house at $7,500, and the inside\nhouses at about $7,200. Each house will\nbe three storiez and cellar, and contain\nten rooms, and be heated with hot water,\nThey will be 22 feet front, each of\ncolonial design, and be what are known as\n\u201cbox houses''\u2014two rooms in front and\ntwo rooms in the rear, which will give\nall the rooms ample light.\nFisher Co, have sold two lots on Mec\nKinley street in Chevy Chase, D. C., to\nErnest H. Elliot, of the Treasury De\npartment, The price paid was 33 cents a\nsquare foot. Mr. Elliot expects to start\nthe erection of his house within the next\nsix months.\nEXPERT IN RENTALS,\nJOHN W. CHILDRESS,\nSecretary and treasurer of Barnard\nChildress, came to Washington about\nthree years ago from Nashville, Tenn. On\nhis arrival here he was connected with\nStone Fairfax as salesman for a time.\nMr. Childress has made a careful study\nof the rental! business in Washington, and\nit was largely due to this knowledge and\nexperience that the new firm was formed\nabout;a year ago to manage tue rental\nof several apartment houses. Mr. Chil\ndress is twenty-nine years old and mar.\nried.\nSANSBURY SELLS LOTS.\nM. H. Bray Breaks Ground for Five\nHouses in Saul's Addition.\nMr. Lisner had a hopeful idea of the ge i Very much Gir\n3\nSe Shen Lig le de da\nThe office of N. C. Sansbury sold seven\nlots in Saul's Addition during the past\nweek, at an average price of $2,000 each.\nA majority of the purchasers will at once\nerect detached houses for their own oc\ncupancy.\nresults during the present year than ever process of manufacture to spirit feceiver\nbefore, its varied from 13 fo 18 over\ncha ahi verproof.\nM. H. Bray, the builder, broke ground\nduring the week for five two-story, eight\nroom houses in this addition. They are\nto be detached, and wili range in price\nfrom $5,000 to $6,000,\nMr. Sansbury also sold to C. B. Wait\nthe large lot situated at the southwest\ncorner of Fifteenth and Delafield streets\nin Saul's Addition. It is the intention of\nthe purchaser to erect on the property a\nmodern ten-room residence which he will\noccupy as his summer home when com\npleted. The price paid for the ground is\nunderstood to have been $2,500\nWHISKY IN BRITAIN\nR.J. Wynne Writes on Trade\nin Distilled Liquors.\nPRODUCT 50,317,908 GALLONS\nScotland Has 150 Distilling Plants,\nIreland 27, and England S~Con\nsumption is 74 Gallons Per Capita.\nKingdom Produced 7,341,077 Gal\nlons for the Export Trade,\nConsul General Robert J, Wynne sends\nto the State Depargnent some interest\ning facts about the British whisky trade.\nHis review covers the amounts distilled\nin England, Scotland, and Ireland, the\nmaterials used, and his general observa\ntions upon the conditions which surround\nthe business of production and distribu\ntion. In part he says:\nThe net amount of duty received on\nBritish spirits for the last year was $56,\n356,650, England contributing $32,926,174,\nScotland $33,500,680, and Ireland $19,839.79.\nThe quantity of spirits made during last\nyear was 50,317,908 proof gallons, England\nfurnishing 13,424,554, Scotland 24,839,870, and\nIreland 12,053,184. The estimated con\n\u2018sumption of spirits per head of the popu\nlation works out at 0.74 proof gallon per\nhead for the whole population.\nThat figure is arrived at by dividing the\ntotal number of proof gallons of spirits\non which duty was paid and passed out\nof the revenue control by the estimated\npopulation for a particular date, ailow\nance being made for duty-paid spirits\nwhich come back into revenue control\nand on which a drawback has been paid.\nConsumption includes stocks laid down\nin cellars and everything of that kind.\nThere would be a considerable quantity\nwasted and a certain amount would go\nfor other purposes.\nNumber of Distilleries,\nThe actual number of distilleries in the\ndifferent parts of the United Kingdom\nnow working is: In England, 8; Scotland,\n150; Ireland, 27. In addition to these, there\nare in England not working, 1; in Scot\nland, 12, and in Ireland, 3.\nThe materials used in the manufac\nture of British spirits were malt, unmalt\ned grain, including corn, barley, oats, rye,\nand wheat, rice, molasses, glucose, sugar,\nsago, tapioca, and other substances such\nas bran and malt combings. (Malt comb\nings are the rootlets of the malted grain\nwhich break off while the malt Is being\ndried in the kiln.) The last two men\ntioned were not really spirit-producing\nmaterials, but were employed maliniy to\npromote fermentation. There was no re\nstriction ag to the materials which might\nbe used for the production of spirit so\nlong as the specific gravity of the worts\nproduced could be ascertained by the hy\ndrometer. The quantities used of the dif\nferent materials in the last distilling\nyear were as lollows:\nBRA 2\nMaterials Used in Ireland\nNo other kinds of materials are used in\nIreland. The totals of the foregoing ma\nterials are: Malt, 1143.9% quarters: un\n\u2018maited grain, 1,136,075 quarters; molasses,\n1,50 hundredweight, and other mate.\nrials, 15,034 hundredweight.\nThe average production of spirits from\neach class of material is, in gallons, as\nfollows:\n0 oS aa lB\nUnmalted grain, per quarter.......................\nSago, per hundredweight...........ccooovvuvnnnns\nTapioca, per hundredweight...........ooovviinnnn..,\nBugar, per hundvedweight............c.ooocvininnnes\nMolasses, per hundredweight............cooc0vinnes\nGlucose, per hundredweight.........................\nFurther statistics showed that in Eng\nland only about one-fourth of the spirit\nproduced was made from malt, in Scot\nland 58.4 per cent was made from malt,\nand in Ireland 31.6 per cent Taking the\nUnited Kingdom as a whole, the pro\nduction of spirits was 39.3 per cent from\nmalt, 474 per cent from unmalted grain,\nand 13.3 per cent from molasses.\nMost of the spirit made from molasses\nwas used for methylation or for indus\ntrial purposes. There were two kinds of\nmethylated spirit. One of these cantained\n5 per cent of methyi alcohol mixed with\nit, and the other, was mineralized methy\nlated spirit, which contained 10 per cent\nof methyl alcohol and three-eighths of 1\nper cent of mineral naphtha. The first\nwas only allowed to be used by persons\nspecially authorized by the commission\ners of inland revenue, but the latter\ncould be used by anybody and was the\nsort usually sold in the oil shops. Some\nmolasses spirit was used for blending\nfor drinking purposes, but not very much,\nStrength of English Whisky,\nEnglish-raade spirits were largely used\nby rectifiers and compounders for mak\ning gin, and compounds, such as cherry\nbrandy, cherry whisky, ginger, sioe gin,\npeppermint, and fruit cordials, and also\nfor tinctures for medicinal purposes.\n\u2018Both pot-still and patent-still disti]\nlerles used unmalted grain. In the latter\nthe principal grain was corn, but oats,\nbarley, and rye were also employed, as\nwell as sago and taploca, About twenty\nfive distilleries devoted themselves large\nly to the manufacture of yeast for sale.\nSome of these produced from twenty to\nproof, and where there\ntillatior. it varied from\ntilled as a rule, d consequently it\nranged between 40 and 50 overproof. When\nbonded the spirit in Scotland was 11\noverproof, and in Ireland about 25 ever\nproof. By law the distiller might bond at\nany strength not below 20 nunderproof or\nabove overproof. Spirits were bonded\nat different strengths to suit circum\nsta) .ces.\nQuantities of Spirits in Stock,\nWith regard to patent stills, fusel oil\nwas rather a valuable by-product, and\nwas used principally for solvent purposes,\nas well as for a special kind of varnish,\nbeing sold at $1.22 a gallon. From the\npatent stills they ran the spirits continu\nously at a strength of 65 or even 69 over\nproof. That strength could not be ob\ntained from pot-stills, The spirit was re\nduced in strength oniy by the addition of\nwater. The spirit wag removed from the\nreceiver to the spirit store under the\nlocks of the excise authorities.\nThe quantity of spirits in store on\nwhich duty was paid last year was 1,286,\n912 proof gallons in England, 205,270 in\nScotland, and %,418 in Ireland. Irish\nwhisky was more expensive than Scotch,\npartly because of the difference in the\nstrength. I.ast year there were 6055285\nproof gallons of British spirits methyl.\nated. The quantity of spirits now in\nbonded warehouses is stated as 10,867,100\nproof gallons in England, 118,977,707 gal\nlons in Scotland, and 81,773,593 gallons in\nIreland. The amount of bonded whisky\nhas been decreasing during the past four\nVears.\nThe export trade of British spirits is an\nimportant one, the quantity exported last\nvear being 7,341,077 proof gallons, and the\nbusiness seems to be on the increase.\nPatent-stilled spirit was cheaper than\npot-stilled because of the larger propor\nlion of corn which it contained.\nWHEAT CROP IN ARGENTINA\nEnormous Yield Upsets the Judg\nment of Speculators.\nQuick Return to Prosperity Indi\ncated by the Fall in Price of\nWorld's Great Staple,\nAbout the opening of the year wheat\nsold in Chicago and New York at \u00a71 a\nbushel. The high point of January was\n$1.05. At that time the bulls were very\naggressive, the financial press was full\nof predictions that wheat would sell at\n$1.25 before the beginning of May. Eng\nlish opinion was sven more positive than\nAmerican that a great bull market in\nwheat was pendinz, and that the price\ncould not fall below $1 before the next\nharvest, and not then unless the North\nAmerican crop should be a record\nbreaking one.\nThis judgment of the speculative world\nseemed justified and the rosy opinions of\nthe winter were undoubtedly sincere and\n\u2018based upon the best information then at\ntainable.\nBut in the face of these predictions spot\nwheat had declined in New York by Feb\nruary 18 to 97 3-8 cents a bushel, but even\nthen the courage of the bulls did not\nwaver, and before the close of February\nthe price had rallied to $1.05. Since then,\nhowever, the course of prices has been\ncontinuously downward to cents and\nstill going lower. It is quite probable\nthat by the beginning of May wheat may\nfall below 9% cents.\nThe explanation of it all is found in\nthe great crop of wheat harvested in the\nArgentine Republic during the three\nmonths from January 1 to March 31, and\nnow being delivered to the markets of\nthe world, Just how big this crop is\ncan be discovered from the recent totals\ncabled from Buenos Ayres last week. The\nofficial crop for Argentina is given at\n202,000,000 bushels, as compared with 152,\n000,000 in 1907 and 140,000,000 in 1908. The\nofficial export figures for the three\nmonths ended March 31 are given at\n64,000,000 this year, as compared with\n45,800,000 last year, and 34,000,000 in 1908.\nIt is now expected that Argentina will\nthrow into the world's market at least\n120,009,000 bushels of wheat, most of it\nbefore the American, Canadian, and Rus\nsian harvests are available. In fact, the\naverage weekly shipments of wheat\nfrom Argentina for the past two months\nhas been 4925000 bushels, and this\namount will increase rather than dimin\nish during the month of May,\nThis means an enormous flow of gold\nto Argentina for one thing, and it is\nlikely to affect in some measure the gute\nput of spring wheat in the great North\nwest, though it is thought by many that\ntae real proportions of the Argentina crop\nwere not known there soon enough to\nhead off the impulse of high prices in\nJanuary and February.\nWhat will be the effect of a great har\nvest in the United States and Canada,\nto which everybody seems to be looking\nforward at the present time? It wiil\nmean lower prices for cereals, much mon\ney for the wheat-producing territory, and\nthe quickest possible return of prosperity\nafter the recent financial depression in\nall parts of the world.\nClasses. Produe.\nMALL, DOF GUAMER............ or iinsaramis ins\nCanadians Like Our Cured Meats.\nAccording to Consul Johy E, Hamilton,\nof Cornwall, Canada, there is a great de\nmand for American cured hams, bacon,\nand lard. Several large sales have been\nmade, and the demand Increases. This\nseems to prove that the hams, lard, and\nbacon cured in the United States are\nmore appreciated than the Canadian\nproducts. The hams and bacon particu\nlarly are well cured, yet not dried up,\namd the lard is clear. Canadians can get\nthese excellent goods for less money and\ncan sell at lower rates, although having\nto pay a 2 cent per pound duty, as well as\nfreight charges.\nMexico Alds Steamship Line.\nAccording to a Mexico City paper, the\nMexican government has granted a sub\nvention of $1,000 a round trip to a steam\nship line which will ply between Galves\nton, Tex., and points in the state of Ta\nbasco. Two trips per month are to be\nmade. The transportation company agrees\nto cultivate and develop the banana and\nother tropleal fruit trade, it being stated\nthat many Americans have also started\nfruit euiture on the banks of Tabascan\nrivers. tas\nBuys Three Houses in Southwest.\nBoss Phelps have sold premises 920\nD street and 925 and 927 Liberty street\ngouthwest to Alfred Boswell, who will\nretain the properties as an investment.\nThe houses stand opposite the new freight\nyards of the Pennsylvania Railroad Com.\nDANY.\nBUILDING IS LIVELY\nIN ALL DIRECTIONS\nn\nMany Houses Are Under Con\nstruction This Year.\nGATCHELLSTARTS STORE\nNorthern Suburbs Invites Num\nber of Homeseekers.\nSeveral Rows Going Up in Four.\nteenth Street and on Site of the\nSchuetzen Park\u2014City Crowds Out\nward to All Points of Compass,\nCounties of Virginia Receiving Ace\ncessions to Rurai Population,\nBuilding operations in the District are\ngoing on with greater activity than for\ntwo years, eliminating the work upon the\npublic structures. More houses are under\nconstruction this year than for any simij\nlar period since the beginning of the\ncontroversy between the workmen and\nthe building trades, While the majority\nof residences are of lesser cost than\nmay have been the case at other times,\nthe number is sufficiently large to war\nrant attention.\nAlong Fourteenth street, from the buse\niness section out to Saul's Addition and\nbeycnd, the sound of the saw end hammer\nis almost constant. Several contractors,\nincluding Mr. Libscomb and Harry Ward\nnan, are constructing rows of houses in\nFourteenth street, and the activity there\nis duplicated along Monroe street and\nother inters\u00e9cting streets. Plans are out\nfor as many as 20 houses in thiz par\nticular quarter this year.\nBuilding in Saul's Addition,\nIn Baul's Addition six houses are under\nconstruction, all of them detached and\nin the n.ore costly class. Along Bright\nwood avenue, from the Loop to Takoma\nPark, and beyond that in the newer sub\ndivisions of Maryland, building operations\nare going forward at a rapid rate. The\nstyle of construction is of the mod\u00e9rate\npriced dsweiling, some of frame and some\nof brick. Schuetzen Park is just now the\nscene of great activity. One row of\nhouses on a side street is nearing com\npletion and another has been started on\nBrightwood avenue. These are houses\nwhich will sell around $,00 when com\npieted.\nAll along the Brightwood road single\nhouses are being built by individuals for\nhomes. In Petworth the large cutput of\nlast year is not being duplicated, but ten\nor more detached houses are under con\nstruction or are about finished. Several\nmore are to be built in the near future.\nIn Brightwood Park, in Brightwood, and\nShe subdivision beyond, the same activity\n\nWilk Bunld in Sixteenth Street,\nAlong Sixteenth street preparations are\nmaking for large building operations this\nyear. Just beyond Florida avenue ex\nSenator and Mrs. Henderson, who have\nput up several fine residences in the last\ntwo years, are contemplating more build\ning. The approaches to the new bridge\nacross Piney Branch have been practically\ncompleted, and the holders of land on\neither side of the street are looking for\nward to extensive operations in the near\nfuture.\nBetween Sixteenth street and Rock\nCreek Park, and in the territory between\nFourteenth street and the Zoo Park many\nnew houses will be constructed this year,\nSome are now going up.\nOutside Connecticut avenue, on both\nsides of the new bridge, building is pro\ngressing faster, if possible, than for two\nyears past. Several new rows have beer\ncompleted recently beyond Rock Creek,\none of which is shown in one of the il\nlustrations in this section.\nGatchell\u2019s New Apartment House.\nRemodeling old structures and fitting up\nnew business properties is progressing ia\nFourteenth street to a marked degree. J.\nFred Gatchell has begun improvements\nto the premises #20 Fourteenth street,\nwhere he is tearing down the present\nhouse and rebuilding entirely throughout.\nThe first floor will be used as his tailor\ning establishment, which will be the\nlargest one in town, covering an area of\n2000 squarn feet, embracing sales, cut\nting, and ftting departments,\nThese departments will be very attrac\ntive In their finish of \u201cmission\u201d oak,\nwith the details pertaining thereto. Thera\nwill be a balcony between the first and\nsecond floor, with large skylight and good\nventilation. The front of the store is pro\nvided with a large show window of plate\nglass, with transoms overhead, and along\neither side will be the show cases and\ndressing rooms.\nThe three stories above the store will\nbe converted into bachelor apartments,\ntwelve in number, with baths, Every\ncomfort and convenience has been pro\nvided in the apartments, which are fin\nished in the most attractive manner.\nAbove the plate glass in the front of\nthe first floor is an ornamental bay win\ndow extending through the second and\nthird stories. The fourth floor will have\nlarge windows opening on a balcony, and\nthe whole will be topped out with an\nornamental cornice. With the exception\nof the two side balusters, the entire front\nwill be finished in copper.\nFrank H. Jackson is the architect, and\nJones Peters the contractors and build.\nTS.\nTiie cost of the building will be $20,000.\nNorthwest Suburbs Growing.\nHouse construction is going on notice\nably all along Wisconsin avenue and in\nadjacent territory. The rapid develop\nnent of this territory shows no abate\nnent, both within the District and in the\new subdivisions in Maryland. Out the\nCabin John way the same Is true. New\n1ouses are under construction along both\nides of the Conduit road, in Glen Echo,\nind wherever the suburban home builder\ninds a location to suit his taste and\nyurse.\nSpace Is pretty weli exhausted in\n3loomingdale and Eckington, but in both\nome of the vacant lots are being built\n1pow this year. Along Rhode Island ave\nue, building operations are particularly\nictive. This holds true beyond Ecking\nand the subdivisions of North Lange\nMount Rainier, and others are show\nng good progress in the multiplication\nf new houses. In the northeast section,\n8 well as in the southeast, new rows\nre appearing on vacant lots that the\nwners 4 few years ago almost despaired\nAcross the Anacostia, from Kenilworth\nround to Congress Heights, the land is\nton,\ndon,\n\nContinued on Page 2, Column 6,","height":"39824","width":"27368"}}
